06247nam a22009975i 9780520940390DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20052005cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209403907 a10.1525/97805209403902doi  a(DE-B1597)519147  a(OCoLC)475933518  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aE185.93.F5 7aHIS0360002bisacsh04a305.896/0730759/090342221 aOrtiz, Paul, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEmancipation Betrayed :bThe Hidden History of Black Organizing and White Violence in Florida from Reconstruction to the Bloody Election of 1920 /cPaul Ortiz. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (430 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAmerican Crossroads ;v1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tList of Tables -- tPreface: Election Day in Florida -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrologue: Slavery and Civil War -- t1. The Promise Of Reconstruction -- t2. The Struggle To Save Democracy -- t3. We Are In The Hands Of The Devil -- t4. To Gain These Fruits That Have Been Earned -- t5. To See That None Suffer -- t6. Looking For A Free State To Live In -- t7. Echoes Of Emancipation -- t8. With Babies In Their Arms -- t9. Election Day, 1920 -- tConclusion: Legacies Of The Florida Movement -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this penetrating examination of African American politics and culture, Paul Ortiz throws a powerful light on the struggle of black Floridians to create the first statewide civil rights movement against Jim Crow. Concentrating on the period between the end of slavery and the election of 1920, Emancipation Betrayed vividly demonstrates that the decades leading up to the historic voter registration drive of 1919-20 were marked by intense battles during which African Americans struck for higher wages, took up arms to prevent lynching, forged independent political alliances, boycotted segregated streetcars, and created a democratic historical memory of the Civil War and Reconstruction. Contrary to previous claims that African Americans made few strides toward building an effective civil rights movement during this period, Ortiz documents how black Floridians formed mutual aid organizations—secret societies, women's clubs, labor unions, and churches—to bolster dignity and survival in the harsh climate of Florida, which had the highest lynching rate of any state in the union. African Americans called on these institutions to build a statewide movement to regain the right to vote after World War I. African American women played a decisive role in the campaign as they mobilized in the months leading up to the passage of the Nineteenth Amendment. The 1920 contest culminated in the bloodiest Election Day in modern American history, when white supremacists and the Ku Klux Klan violently, and with state sanction, prevented African Americans from voting. Ortiz's eloquent interpretation of the many ways that black Floridians fought to expand the meaning of freedom beyond formal equality and his broader consideration of how people resist oppression and create new social movements illuminate a strategic era of United States history and reveal how the legacy of legal segregation continues to play itself out to this day.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszFloridaxHistory. 0aAfrican AmericanszFloridaxPolitics and governmenty19th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszFloridaxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aAfrican AmericanszFloridaxSocial conditions. 0aRacismzFloridaxHistoryy19th century. 0aRacismzFloridaxHistoryy20th centu